    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>(Private)</p>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Cleved</placeName>
                <date>Nov 16<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1854</date>
            </p>
            <p>Rev &amp; Dear Friend</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">In my last letter<lb/> I informed you of a contempla<lb/>-ted
                movement among our people<lb/> having in view the union of<lb/> the two
                congregations—in order<lb/> to secure better religious &amp;<lb/> educational
                advantages for<lb/> both adults &amp; children</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I was unable to give you<lb/> then the real objects,
                entertained<lb/> by those most zealous for the<lb/> proposed consolidation.
                Since<lb/> the meeting of the committees<lb/> and their preliminary reports<lb/> to
                both Kabals—the real<lb/> intentions have become maini<lb/>-fest and these I
                propose<lb/> to make known to you.</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>Let me premise by saying the<lb/> present condition of both Kabals<lb/> educationally
                considered is deplora<lb/>-ble, at least in the light of the<lb/> advanced progress
                of the Age.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Now it is proposed by the zealots<lb/> to build a new
                Synagogue—first<lb/> disposing of one or both of the<lb/> existing structures &amp;
                have its<lb/> interior constructed for family<lb/> pews—for male &amp; female—to
                adopt<lb/> a new minhag—engage a reform<lb/> preacher &amp; in a word go the
                whole<lb/> figure <hi rend="underline">a la <persName>Dr Wise</persName></hi>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">In the limits of a letter I cannot<lb/> give you an adequate idea of
                the<lb/> wishes &amp; intentions of the so called<lb/> reformers. Let me say that
                a<lb/> very large number if not quite<lb/> a majority of the members of<lb/> both
                societies are ready &amp; anxious</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>to adopt these views &amp; projects<lb/> unless speedily enlightened as to<lb/> their
                apostasy. The only saving<lb/> clause to us for I class myself<lb/> among those who
                will resist<lb/> to the utmost this wholesale<lb/>
                <del>ann</del> system of innovation to<lb/> use no harsher term—is that<lb/> if a
                majority of both societies<lb/> determine to adopt these doc-<lb/>-trines we can
                restrain them<lb/> from selling the property as we<lb/> own &amp; possess in good
                title<lb/> seats <hi rend="underline">forever</hi> in the respective buildings &amp;
                they do not propose<lb/> to allow us for these any com-<lb/>pensation or return
                either whole<lb/> or in part in the new edifice.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I have looked up the legal<lb/> authorities on this point
                besides<lb/> taking the benefit of counsel.</p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>Now I am willing &amp; ready to surrender<lb/> all real &amp; personal interest I own
                in the<lb/> synagogue &amp; unite with the other society<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">provided</hi>—there shall be no overreacting<lb/> and departure
                from the limits of enlight<lb/>-ened orthodoxy.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I am in favor of a<lb/> preacher of enlightened views—a school-<lb/>
                of doing away with certain customs<lb/> (mere forms)—of repetition of prayers—<lb/>
                and of other sensible modifications,<lb/> but I decline to reject the belief in<lb/>
                a personal messiah &amp; the resurrection<lb/> of the body. These I hold as
                funda<lb/>-mental principles of our faith that<lb/> cannot be abolished or
                abandoned.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Now with reference to Pews—<lb/> I believe neither the Pentateuch
                nor Prophets speak<lb/> advisedly on this point—the only reason<lb/> for the
                    <sic>seperation</sic> of the sexes I have<lb/> ever heard advanced &amp; have
                entertained<lb/> myself have been with reference to cleanli<lb/>-ness &amp; the
                reverse at certain periods<lb/> in the other sex. Understand me<lb/> though—that
                while I say this to you</p>
            <pb n="5"/>
            <p rend="align(center)">5.</p>
            <p>privately<lb/> I maintain publicly an observance of the old<lb/> custom that is I
                have already done<lb/> so in more than one speech on the<lb/> subject. Now I want
                your advice<lb/> on this point and <hi rend="underline">arguments</hi> to<lb/>
                sustain my public position for my<lb/> private conviction rather favor the<lb/>
                mingling of both sexes in the Synagogue<lb/> on an equality. It is true—it
                    <del>is</del> assim<lb/>-ilates in form to Christian mode<lb/> of worship—but
                    <add>?</add> devotion<lb/> if only apparent is not wanting<lb/> in the
                appearance of their Congre<lb/>-gations. Give me some good solid<lb/> reasons or law
                why they should not<lb/> sit together. I wish it was in<lb/> my power to have the
                benefit<lb/> of your society for at least two<lb/> hours—that we might go over<lb/>
                all these points. I stand in<lb/> need of confirmation of assistance</p>
            <pb n="6"/>
            <p>of counsel of authorities etc etc.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">My mind misgives on many points<lb/> advanced in favor of change.
                I<lb/> see much that might be adopted<lb/> with benefit—much that would<lb/> cause
                    <placeName>Israel</placeName> to depart eventually<lb/> from its ancient
                faith.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">The reformers in our Congrega-<lb/>-tion are <persName>Solomon
                    Hyman</persName>—<persName>Alex<lb/> Schwab</persName>—<persName>Mosely
                    Ezekiel</persName>—<persName>Solomon<lb/> Mann</persName> &amp; <persName>Messrs
                    Steiner</persName>—<persName>Bloch</persName>—<lb/>
                <persName>Platt</persName> &amp; <persName>Nusbaum</persName>. Those who<lb/> oppose
                these besides myself are<lb/>
                <persName>Messrs Ga Davis</persName>
                <persName>F I. Cohen</persName>
                <persName>Jacob Cohen</persName><lb/>
                <persName>D Cauffman</persName>
                <persName>C &amp; A Loeb</persName>. <persName>C Koeh</persName><lb/>
                <persName>E. Cohen</persName> which <persName>I A Isaacs</persName>
                <persName>B. Shribe</persName><lb/> &amp; <persName>M Liebenthal</persName> are not
                to be relied<lb/> on for anything.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Will you break away<lb/> from your numerous duties for an<lb/> hour
                &amp; give me the benefit of your</p>
            <pb n="7"/>
            <p>counsel &amp; experience. Oh, would it<lb/> were I could see you. I study the<lb/>
                law constantly but my duties will<lb/> not allow me time to grasp hold of<lb/> all I
                could wish to explore &amp; examine<lb/> &amp; determine &amp; then being <hi
                    rend="underline">all</hi> alone<lb/> I fear to rely singly on my own
                judge-<lb/>-ment lest it lead me astray.<lb/> A few years more study will
                de-<lb/>-termine my mind but these years<lb/> must be directed in a measure<lb/> by
                better wisdom than that<lb/> which now falls to my share.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Please write me speedily<lb/> &amp; greatly oblige</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Your very true &amp; Sincere friend</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">
                <persName role="author">B F. Peixotto</persName>
            </p>
        </body>
